---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';

const canonicalUrl = 'https://handheldsettings.com/guides/usb-c-power-bank-wattage-handheld-gaming/';
const title = 'Steam Deck power bank requirements and airline rules — Handheld Settings Lab';
const description = 'Choose a Steam Deck power bank by USB-C PD wattage and watt-hours, then pack it correctly for U.S. flights using current FAA and TSA guidance.';

const sourceLinks = [
  { label: 'Valve: Steam Deck technical specifications', url: 'https://www.steamdeck.com/en/tech' },
  { label: 'FAA PackSafe: lithium batteries', url: 'https://www.faa.gov/hazmat/packsafe/lithium-batteries' },
  { label: 'TSA: power banks', url: 'https://www.tsa.gov/travel/security-screening/whatcanibring/items/power-banks' },
  { label: 'USB-IF: USB Power Delivery overview', url: 'https://www.usb.org/usb-charger-pd' }
];

const shoppingLinks = [
  { label: '45W+ USB-C PD power banks under 100Wh', href: 'https://www.amazon.com/s?k=45w+usb+c+pd+power+bank+under+100wh', category: 'power-banks' },
  { label: '65W USB-C PD power banks with Wh label', href: 'https://www.amazon.com/s?k=65w+usb+c+pd+power+bank+watt+hours', category: 'power-banks' },
  { label: '100W USB-C PD cables', href: 'https://www.amazon.com/s?k=100w+usb+c+pd+cable', category: 'cables-adapters' }
];

const faqs = [
  {
    question: 'What wattage power bank does a Steam Deck need?',
    answer: 'Valve lists a 45W USB-C PD 3.0 power supply. A power bank should therefore provide a dedicated USB-C Power Delivery output in the 45W class or higher. A 65W bank is a flexible choice, but the Steam Deck negotiates the power it supports rather than being forced to take the bank’s full rating.'
  },
  {
    question: 'Can I bring a Steam Deck power bank on a plane?',
    answer: 'Under current U.S. FAA and TSA guidance, power banks containing lithium-ion batteries belong in carry-on baggage, not checked baggage. Protect the terminals and remove the bank if a carry-on is checked at the gate. Always check the airline and destination-country rules as well.'
  },
  {
    question: 'Is a 20,000 mAh power bank allowed on a plane?',
    answer: 'Capacity must be judged by the battery’s watt-hour rating, not mAh alone. A typical 20,000 mAh pack using 3.6–3.7V cells is roughly 72–74Wh and therefore below the FAA’s 100Wh threshold, but the printed Wh rating on the product is the value to verify.'
  },
  {
    question: 'Is a 27,000 mAh power bank under 100Wh?',
    answer: 'It can be very close to the limit: 27Ah multiplied by 3.6V is 97.2Wh, while 27Ah multiplied by 3.7V is 99.9Wh. Do not infer eligibility from the marketing capacity. Use the manufacturer’s clearly printed watt-hour rating and leave behind a bank whose rating cannot be verified.'
  },
  {
    question: 'Will a 65W power bank damage a Steam Deck?',
    answer: 'A standards-compliant USB-C PD source and device negotiate a supported power profile. The 65W number is the bank’s available maximum, not power that is automatically pushed into the Deck. Cable quality and explicit USB-C PD support still matter.'
  },
  {
    question: 'Why does Steam Deck show a slow charger warning with my power bank?',
    answer: 'The bank may not offer the required USB-C PD profile on that port, its output may drop when another device is connected, the cable may be limited, or the pack may be low or hot. Test the dedicated high-output USB-C port with a known-good PD cable and no second device attached.'
  }
];

const jsonLd = [
  {
    '@context': 'https://schema.org',
    '@type': 'TechArticle',
    headline: 'Steam Deck power bank requirements and airline rules',
    description,
    url: canonicalUrl,
    datePublished: '2026-07-21',
    dateModified: '2026-07-21',
    author: { '@type': 'Organization', name: 'Handheld Settings Lab' },
    publisher: { '@type': 'Organization', name: 'Handheld Settings Lab', url: 'https://handheldsettings.com/' },
    about: ['Steam Deck', 'USB-C Power Delivery', 'power banks', 'air travel']
  },
  {
    '@context': 'https://schema.org',
    '@type': 'BreadcrumbList',
    itemListElement: [
      { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 1, name: 'Home', item: 'https://handheldsettings.com/' },
      { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 2, name: 'Guides', item: 'https://handheldsettings.com/guides/' },
      { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 3, name: 'Steam Deck power bank and airline guide', item: canonicalUrl }
    ]
  },
  {
    '@context': 'https://schema.org',
    '@type': 'FAQPage',
    mainEntity: faqs.map(faq => ({
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: faq.question,
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: faq.answer }
    }))
  }
];
---
<Base title={title} description={description} jsonLd={jsonLd}>
  <article class="wrap article">
    <span class="eyebrow">Steam Deck power and flight guide</span>
    <h1>Steam Deck power bank requirements and airline rules</h1>
    <p class="muted">For a Steam Deck, output wattage determines whether the pack can properly power the handheld; watt-hours determine flight eligibility and approximate stored energy. This is official-source-informed buying and packing guidance, not a hands-on runtime test.</p>
    <p class="affiliate-note">Disclosure: shopping links are broad Amazon searches marked sponsored/nofollow, not product endorsements. We have not claimed hands-on testing, and the site adds an Associates tag only when a real tag is configured.</p>

    <div class="callout"><strong>Short answer:</strong> choose a clearly labeled USB-C PD power bank with at least 45W from one USB-C port and a printed rating no higher than 100Wh for the simplest U.S. air-travel case. Pack it in your carry-on, not your checked bag.</div>

    <h2>The two numbers that matter</h2>
    <div class="grid cols2">
      <section class="card">
        <span class="chip">Charging speed</span>
        <h3>45W USB-C PD output</h3>
        <p>Valve lists a PD 3.0 Type-C power supply at 45W. Match that class from one USB-C output. A bank advertising 65W total across three ports is not enough evidence if no single port delivers the needed PD output.</p>
      </section>
      <section class="card">
        <span class="chip">Flight capacity</span>
        <h3>100Wh or less</h3>
        <p>The FAA limits ordinary passenger lithium-ion batteries to 100 watt-hours per battery. With airline approval, up to two larger spare batteries in the 101–160Wh range may be carried. A power bank is treated as a spare battery.</p>
      </section>
    </div>

    <h2>45W, 65W, or 100W: which output should you buy?</h2>
    <table>
      <thead><tr><th>Bank output</th><th>Steam Deck use</th><th>Who it suits</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Under 45W</td><td>May charge slowly or lose battery while playing</td><td>Phone duty; not the preferred main Deck bank</td></tr>
        <tr><td>45W USB-C PD</td><td>Matches Valve’s listed power-supply class</td><td>Deck-only travel with minimal extra headroom</td></tr>
        <tr><td>65W USB-C PD</td><td>More available power than the Deck’s listed adapter class; the devices negotiate</td><td>A practical shared bank for a Deck and many other handhelds</td></tr>
        <tr><td>100W USB-C PD</td><td>Not required solely for Steam Deck</td><td>One bank shared with a compatible laptop, dock, or higher-power device</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p>A higher advertised maximum does not make the Deck charge beyond its negotiated input. It can still be useful for other hardware, but output wattage and battery capacity are different specifications: a “100W” bank can still be under the 100Wh flight threshold.</p>

    <h2>Airline checklist for a Steam Deck power bank</h2>
    <ol>
      <li><strong>Find the printed Wh rating.</strong> Photograph the label before travel. Do not rely on an online listing after you reach security.</li>
      <li><strong>Keep it in carry-on baggage.</strong> TSA says power banks are allowed in carry-on bags and prohibited in checked bags.</li>
      <li><strong>Remove it from a gate-checked bag.</strong> FAA guidance says spare lithium batteries and power banks must stay with the passenger in the cabin if a carry-on is checked planeside.</li>
      <li><strong>Protect against short circuits.</strong> Keep the bank from loose metal objects and protect exposed terminals or connectors.</li>
      <li><strong>Check the airline and route.</strong> The FAA/TSA rules cited here are U.S. guidance. Airlines and destination countries may impose additional restrictions or in-flight-use rules.</li>
      <li><strong>Do not travel with damage.</strong> Leave behind a swollen, punctured, recalled, overheating, or otherwise defective battery.</li>
    </ol>

    <h2>Convert mAh to Wh without guessing</h2>
    <p>Airline limits use watt-hours. When the manufacturer provides both milliamp-hours and the battery’s nominal voltage, the relationship is:</p>
    <div class="callout"><strong>Wh = (mAh ÷ 1,000) × nominal battery voltage</strong></div>
    <table>
      <thead><tr><th>Advertised capacity</th><th>Example nominal voltage</th><th>Calculated energy</th><th>What to do</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>20,000 mAh</td><td>3.6–3.7V</td><td>72–74Wh</td><td>Verify the bank’s printed Wh label</td></tr>
        <tr><td>26,800 mAh</td><td>3.7V</td><td>99.16Wh</td><td>Very close to the limit; label clarity matters</td></tr>
        <tr><td>27,000 mAh</td><td>3.6–3.7V</td><td>97.2–99.9Wh</td><td>Do not assume; use the manufacturer rating</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p>These are arithmetic examples, not capacity-test results. Cell arrangement, label conventions, and conversion losses complicate real delivered energy. The marked watt-hour rating is the relevant travel specification.</p>

    <h2>What runtime should you expect?</h2>
    <p>We do not publish a fixed “extra hours” claim because game draw, frame cap, brightness, wireless use, thermals, battery-pack conversion efficiency, and whether the Deck is charging while playing all change the result. Use the <a href="/calculators/battery-estimator/">battery estimator</a> to model a range rather than treating the bank’s label as energy delivered directly to the game.</p>
    <ul>
      <li>A lower-power game at a capped frame rate generally stretches both the internal battery and external pack further than a demanding game.</li>
      <li>A 20,000 mAh label is not 20,000 mAh delivered at the Deck’s charging voltage.</li>
      <li>Heat and high conversion load can reduce useful output.</li>
      <li>Charging the internal battery and powering active gameplay are not the same workload.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Prevent slow-charger warnings</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Use the bank’s explicitly labeled high-output USB-C PD port.</li>
      <li>Use a cable rated for the intended power; replace an unmarked or intermittent cable before replacing the bank.</li>
      <li>Disconnect a second device because multiport banks may redistribute output.</li>
      <li>Check whether the bank reduces output at low state of charge or high temperature.</li>
      <li>Test the setup before leaving home with the Deck under a real game load.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Spec-based shopping shortlist</h2>
    <div class="grid cols3">
      {shoppingLinks.map(link => (
        <a class="card gear-card" href={link.href} target="_blank" rel="nofollow sponsored" data-affiliate-link data-category={link.category}>
          <span class="chip">Sponsored search</span>
          <h3>{link.label}</h3>
          <p class="muted">Compare the single-port PD output, printed Wh rating, recall status, warranty, size, and recent buyer reports before purchasing.</p>
        </a>
      ))}
    </div>
    <p>For broader comparisons, visit the <a href="/gear/power-banks/">USB-C power bank gear guide</a>, check the <a href="/guides/usb-c-cable-wattage-handheld-gaming/">USB-C cable wattage guide</a>, or return to the <a href="/steam-deck-settings/">Steam Deck settings hub</a> to reduce game power demand.</p>

    <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>
    <div class="grid cols2">
      {faqs.map(faq => (
        <section class="card">
          <h3>{faq.question}</h3>
          <p>{faq.answer}</p>
        </section>
      ))}
    </div>

    <h2>Sources checked</h2>
    <p>Valve, FAA, TSA, and USB-IF public pages were checked on July 21, 2026. FAA and TSA establish the U.S. baggage rules; Valve establishes the Deck’s listed 45W USB-C PD power-supply class. Airline approval remains airline-specific, and travel rules can change.</p>
    <ul>
      {sourceLinks.map(source => <li><a href={source.url} target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener">{source.label}</a></li>)}
    </ul>
  </article>
</Base>
